> Ah, the humble turkey patty. Simple, adaptable, flavorful—seriously, what's not to love? Weeknight win!

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb} until you have 1 TBSP (2 TBSP for 4 servings). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens; mince whites.

Toss broccoli on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon}, @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} with half the @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce} (you'll use the rest later). Add water 1 tsp at a time until sauce reaches a drizzling consistency.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @ground turkey{10%ounce}, ginger, scallion whites, @ponzu sauce{12%milliliters}, @pho stock concentrate{1}, @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, @salt{1/2%tsp} (we used 1 tsp for 4 servings), and pepper. Mix gently until thoroughly combined.

Form into 6 1 1/2-inch balls (12 balls for 4).
> TIP: Rub hands with a little oil first to prevent sticking.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add turkey mixture; gently press down with a #spatula{} to make 1/2-inch-thick patties. (For 4, cook in batches if necessary.) Cook patties until browned and cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} per side.

In a second large bowl, toss together roasted broccoli, @shredded red cabbage{4%ounce}, @sesame dressing{1.5%ounce}, half the scallion greens, and remaining chili sauce. Season with a pinch of salt and pepper.

Divide patties and salad between plates. Drizzle patties with sweet chili mayo and garnish with remaining scallion greens. Serve.